issue_body:
Hi!

I'm using dlib v 19.2.
I took one example from previous issue re the use of compute_lda_transform. The code is presented below. I find the results returning from the function strange:
1) Mean is equal zero, but should not
2) results differs significantly from theones get from R

Could you check and write what is wrong.
How I need to use compute_lda_transform if Ineed to get coordinates of x in a new transformed vector space?

Code example:
#include <dlib/matrix.h>
#include <dlib/rand.h>
#include <dlib/statistics.h>

using namespace dlib;
using namespace std;

int main()
{

	typedef matrix<double, 2, 1> Sample;

	std::vector<unsigned long> labels;
	std::vector<Sample> samples;
	Sample vector_;

	for (int i = 0; i<4; i++) {
		Sample s;
		s(0) = i;
		s(1) = i + 1;
		samples.push_back(s);
		labels.push_back(1);

		Sample s1;
		s1(0) = i + 1;
		s1(1) = i;
		samples.push_back(s1);
		labels.push_back(2);
	}

	matrix<double> X;
	X.set_size(8, 2);
	for (int i = 0; i<8; i++) {
		X(i, 0) = samples[i](0);
		X(i, 1) = samples[i](1);
	}

	matrix<double, 0, 1> mean;

	dlib::compute_lda_transform(X, mean, labels,1);

	cout << "Samples: \n";
	for (int i = 0; i < samples.size(); ++i)
		cout << samples[i](0) << "; "<<samples[i](1) << endl;
	cout << "\n";
	cout << mean << "\n";
	cout << X << "\n";
	for (int i = 0; i<samples.size(); i++) 
	{
		cout << X*samples[i] - mean << "\n";
	}

	cin.get();
	return 0;
	
}

With the following code, I get the message `'namespace_parent.h' does not need to be #included`, which is incorrect.

parent.h
```cpp
namespace parent
{
   class Parent {};
}
```
child.h
```cpp
#include "namespace_parent.h"

using namespace parent;

namespace child
{
   class Child : Parent {};
}
```
The code compiles correctly but 'using namespace' in a header file is bad practice, so it might be better to give a warning that it is better to use full namespaces.

Hi all, remove "print("Okay!")" please

tinydb/tinydb/middlewares.py: line 171

code:

                    for field in item:
                        try:
                            if item[field].startswith(tag):
                                print('Okay!')

It is possible for result to be undefined within the following function causing an error:

    def __add__(self, other):
        try:
            result = self.intersect(other, u=True)
        except BEDToolsError:
            # BEDTools versions <2.20 would raise BEDToolsError
            if (self.file_type == 'empty') or (other.file_type == 'empty'):
                result = pybedtools.BedTool("", from_string=True)
        return result

This happens if an exception is raised and the condition in the except clause is not met.
See also issue com/chapmanb/bcbio-nextgen#1002

